Say I'm writing a feline civilization for a game I may or may not finish.
My idea is that cats are mostly solitary animals, and so they tend not to stick with mates at all. If a female wants kits, she will go out for a night, find a male, get pregnant, and raise the kittens herself.
The concept is that both males and females are so plucky about how they want things at home (their only chance of relaxing after spending all day wageslaving) that they end up constantly at each other's throats. In general, I want to reflect a people that can only function with one person in charge, any "teams" end ups up with the members fighting. They're all individualistic, and tend to challenge "muh status quo", which also kind of ends up with nothing ever getting too big without some dickwad sabotaging it so he can take over.
Is this too unlikable? Both from a story perspective and a romance perspective? It's not like you'd be kept away from your potential kids or whatever, and I feel like it would suit the game better (travelling diplomat/hitman/whatever) if you could just leave mom at home and that be the most natural thing. Of course, if I were to make any progress at all, I'd have to write around this when it comes to more "traditional" cultures, but I'm sure I'll figure that out eventually.
Just more concerned whether this makes the setting actually likable or not, since you'd be heavily involved in what happens to the nation in general.
